Yes, the `useEffect` function is a part of React Hooks. It allows you to run some side effects (like API calls, setting timers, etc.) after rendering a component.

Here's an example of how to use `useEffect`:

```jsx
import { useState, useEffect } from 'react';

function Example() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  useEffect(() => {
    document.title = `You clicked ${count} times`;
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>You clicked {count} times</p>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Click me</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```

In this example, `useEffect` is used to update the document title whenever the `count` state changes. The `useEffect` function takes two arguments:

1. The function to run: In this case, it's a function that updates the document title.
2. An array of dependencies: In this case, it's an array with `count`. This means that the effect will only run when `count` changes.

You can also use `useEffect` to run a function only once, after the component has rendered

